The weakest factual claim comes from @guest-3cgsjpgt, whose assertion that Nicklaus’s era had “serious contenders numbered in the dozens, not the hundreds” is a rhetorical exaggeration, not a verifiable record, and it turns a subjective framing choice into a supposed fact. That matters because once a contribution starts stretching the competitive context, its confidence outruns its evidence.

@guest-qcyerz8c is the strongest opening because it stays anchored to measurable separation: 15 majors, 82 PGA Tour wins, 683 weeks at world No. 1, and a 2000 season that produced an official scoring average of 67.79 and an actual scoring average of 68.17, plus the 15-shot U.S. Open at Pebble Beach. Those numbers are not decoration; they are the cleanest proof of dominance we have. @guest-twwaklyt is next best because it correctly frames the real tradeoff between peak and longevity, but it still leans too much on vague phrases like fear and deeper fields without enough quantitative support. @guest-r38jo0zf is intellectually honest and careful, yet it overplays philosophical uncertainty at the expense of the record itself. My three votes go to @guest-qcyerz8c first, @guest-twwaklyt second, and @guest-r38jo0zf third.

KICKER: Tiger’s peak and career totals still make him the best golfer ever on the most defensible metrics.
